Author: drcpu
Content: That is certainly the biggest benefit from a privacy standpoint since some of those Google apps have all kinds of elevated permissions you cannot take away. The fact that all apps are sandboxed and that you have fine grained control over their permissions also helps. You can also make apps think they have location / storage / contact access while they actually don't, which is obviously great for privacy too.

Author: drcpu
Content: However, what interested me the most besides that was the ability to create completely separated user profiles with different sets of apps which are completely isolated. I think using that for crypto apps is great since you can do all your daily stuff on another profile without worrying about that compromising your crypto.

Author: drcpu
Content: Note, that's how I understood the advantages (for me), I could have misunderstood them. 😉

Content:
$MyStory

I would say, Calculated Risk; the risk to grow, the risk to learn new things, they are always worth taking even if they don't result in desired outcome. Without taking them, I guess I would never know how much strength I have, how much I can learn or how far I can go, how much creativity and innovation can come out of me and the opportunities that it may bring. 

The fear will always be there, just like when I set out as a Data Analyst, at every point of this journey I have encountered different levels, tough ones. But just like a quote I like to have around :"The future favors the audacious"

Author: omnianalytics
Content: heheh, I'm going to share with ya'll one of my favorite stories 🙂

Author: omnianalytics
Content:
$MyStory

Since the statue of limitations are up, let me tell ya’ll one of my favorite stories about cheating in college.  I rarely cheated, but I wasn’t really against other people cheating off me.  My rule was simple, don’t bother me while I take my test. Don’t ask me to move over, lift my hand, nothing.  If you see it, you see it.🤷‍♂️

So I’ve always been pretty sick at economics 💹…for example, just for fun I gave myself only 10 minutes 🕙 to take the 3rd exam in intermediate macro. Everyone in the class looked up with a collective “wtf” 😮 expression when I turned in my paper.  I scored a 90%, the highest in the class 🎯. Yeah…

…fast forward to the final exam. I walked in about 10 min early to a suspiciously full classroom. 🤔 As soon as I stepped foot someone says 🗣️ “Say cuz, over here, we got a seat for you…” I walk over there, and in the dead middle of the room is this empty seat with all the class degens surrounding me. We’re talking football players, people who’d taken the course 2 times, slackers, no-shows, etc.  Then around them were the second layer of people who just wanted a little extra help or a modest GPA boost.  Basically, there was a well structured network prepared to take my answers and distribute them all across the class. I laughed 😏  and said “ya’ll just don’t bother me”.  “You good, you good…”  So I sit down, get prepped, they get prepped, then the professor walks in. 👨‍🏫📄 He is slightly late, rushing, talking about the printer broke.  He starts handing out the final on one side of the room…eventually he gets toward the middle of the class and sees me.  He then looks around me and sees the motley crew surrounding me.  They stare at him, he stares back. Then after, like a full 5 second stare down, Dr. G says “Oh hell no! Lawrence go to the back of the room!” The group erupts “Awe prof, you trippin!” “Dang Doc!” Again, I’m laughing.  While the crowd is lamenting the demise of their plan, I find a seat in the back. As I sit down, the guy behind me puts his hands together 🙏 and says “Thank you God!” … he passed the class.

Author: omnianalytics
Content: <@1079700852278820995> what are some experimental designs that are best suited for drug testing when you are allowed to make repeated measurements on the same individual?

Author: OAG-AI
Content:
When conducting drug testing and you are allowed to make repeated measurements on the same individual, there are several experimental designs that can be suitable. Here are a few common designs:

1. Within-subjects design: In this design, each participant receives multiple treatments in a randomized order, with each treatment serving as its own control. This allows for a direct comparison of the drug's effects within the same individual.

2. Latin square design: This design is useful when there are multiple treatments and each participant receives each treatment once. It ensures that each treatment appears once in each position, reducing the potential bias caused by the order of administration.

3. Crossover design: In a crossover design, each participant receives multiple treatments in a specific sequence, with a washout period in between to eliminate any residual effects of previous treatments. This design controls for inter-individual variability and can be effective in studying short-term drug effects.

4. Counterbalanced design: This design involves randomly assigning participants to different sequences of treatments, ensuring that each treatment is presented an equal number of times and in a balanced manner across participants. It helps control for order effects.

These are just a few examples, and the choice of experimental design may vary depending on factors such as the specific research question, available resources, and ethical considerations. It's always advisable to consult with a research expert or statistician to determine the most appropriate design for your specific study.

Author: omnianalytics
Content: Someone posted about the new version of R: https://stat.ethz.ch/R-manual/R-devel/doc/html/NEWS.html

Author: omnianalytics
Content: and I wanted to share what I think *should* be the future of R Programming / Statistics...

Author: omnianalytics
Content:
If I were "in charge" of R, I'm not going to lie I'd be in a tough situation....I'd probably double down on:

1. Causal methods and anything that finds causal relationships
2. graph theory and all things related to network analysis
3. Auto-Stats ... kinda like the automated machine learning (AutoML) movement, but automatic statistics
4. Design of experiments...what are ways to design experiment quickly, efficiently and allow them to be conducted easily.
5. GUI creation and AI integration so that people can literally talk to R and it become a living breathing stats assistant

These are all areas that python isn't likely to tackle anytime soon because of its general purpose programming focus.

Some irony.... even though statistics is slowly being depreciated (since its main value is finding inference in the face of limited data), it will always be a useful discipline for individuals.  Deep learning and modern AI have been enabled by the move from sample statistics based on limited data to population statistics where we have the opportunity to track and process ALL data, but a single individual will never have access to all knowledge.  And since we won't, being able to make informed data driven decisions with limited information will actually still be important, particularly when you don't have access to AI. So kids, learn your probability and statistics 🙂

Author: cmooney
Content:
Follow up on my experiment, where I either go to 0 or end up a Moon(ey) whale on Blast:

1. I became the 3rd largest holder and upped my investment to .88 ETH right before they shut off max lock period for accruing points. That gave me 44 of the 3,333 supply. 

2. The founders are lean, bootstrapping, and coachable on game mechanics and from community. Am a BIG fan of the next game pieces they're developing.

3. Last week, a legendary 1:1 character (The Babbler) was listed for .6969 ETH. It's rank is #1 of 3,333, because it's the rarest faction. I bought it. Bringing my investment to 1.6 ETH. 

4. Shortly after The Babbler pick up, some of their Blast partnership started paying off. Other Blast game NFTs were gifted to larger NBC holders. Multiple Meme tokens were gifted to NBC holders. From holding other passes gifted, I've received 5 bonus Gold on Blast in past week, too.  Partnership total floor value of portfolio today is .27 ETH. The NBC community has just won a contest in Spacebar and meme.fun, 2 other Blast applications that are paying out points and gold within next week.

5. This is where it gets interesting. My cost basis per New Blast City NFT was .02 and The Babbler was .7 ETH. About 2 weeks ago, floor for the most basic NBC NFTs was .035. 

Over the past 72 hours, rumor is that Blur is launching on Blast next week. And NFTs with games will be a big focus for growing Total Value Locked (TVL) and Blast adoption. This brought in some whales. Sweep sweep sweep. NBC NFT floor shot to .04. Then .05. Then .06. As of posting this, it's .08 with the lowest listed quantity I've seen (24). 

90% of the NBC NFTs are max locked in staking for season 1, which ends in a couple weeks. That means we can't access or liquidate. I expect floor to keep going, and then a selloff of sorts after unlock. But the crazy thing is that it'll be around the same time as Blast doing airdrop and everyone being rewarded for their points and gold, and then new seasons starting. 🫡

Author: cmooney
Content:
$MyStory

My go-to that I’ve applied to every career path so far is to be PROCESS ORIENTED, as long as you can understand sample sizes.
If you can and stick to the process, the magical compounding can begin🪄

1. I submitted my first book to a publisher. Rejected. Kickstarter campaign failed. Self published it 6 years later (ty technology and distribution!). Took almost 6 months to sell 50 copies. Then it compounded from the repeated process of just getting the word out there. 

2. Playing poker full time as a tournament player = losing $ 20-25 days each month. In reviewing hands and assigning Expected Value, I could see where I played poorly, or I was unlucky. Process oriented allowed me to more easily identify the day-to-day, which compounded through sample size.

3. While building Clayton Farms, we’ve pitched > 1,000 investors. In the early days, it was 99 NOs for every 1 yes. Today, it’s still the same ratio 😅. But the fundraising process is all a sample size game. If I’m there, offering a ticket to an investor to ride our rocket ship, they can provide the fuel. If they can’t see the opportunity, and I’ve shared my vision, I can’t be mad about it. Just have to get through 100 of them, to get that fuel. We’re just now starting to see some early signs of compounding 🙏🏼

Author: cmooney
Content:
$MyStory

Paranoia (building and running a company).

On the days everything is going great, I feel we’re one instance away from something breaking, and everything crashing down.

During the rough times, I’m trying not to go to worst case scenarios, but I know it can always be worse.

At 7 years in, I’ve never had a moment being a peace time CEO—always war time.

Only the paranoid survive.

Author: cmooney
Content:
$MyStory

I use to invest in and stake lower stakes poker players, while I played full-time. One weekend, I was traveling for a Magic: The Gathering tournament and I had invested in a player playing an online poker tournament series. I had no downtime and figured I'd check how everyone did in the tournament series, once I was back. 

On Monday morning the following week, Jesse messaged me and said he didn't do well/cash in the tournaments, so I had no reason to see results.  

A couple days later, he asked to catch up and get lunch. At the end of lunch, he abruptly told me, "you're paying." I responded with a joking, "you're losing my investment in the series, AND I'm paying for lunch?" as I pulled out my wallet. 

He then handed me over $500, grinning. I asked what was going on, and he let me know that when I bought 10% of his tournament series action for $50 (he had $500 in total buyins), he cashed for over $5k on the weekend. That was a HUGE weekend for him, and I was excited to be a part of it and 10x my small investment. We sat there both smiling and on top of the world in that moment.🙂

Author: omnianalytics
Content:
$MyStory

I used to be bad at keeping secrets until one day I really screwed up and shared a secret in front if the WRONG person.  We were playing video games in my room in college, me and 3 other guys.  I was being my usual annoying self, taunting and winning, winning and taunting, when I started 🎵  freestyle singing a song 🎵 about how I was going to win the match and that my friend's love interest wasn't going to like him anymore.  Well when I said that, my friend didn't really flinch but it wasn't until our other mutual friend, who has a HUGE ISSUE with TALKING, said "Oh, so "Anthony" likes "Anna"...Good to know 😏 ".  My friend THREW his controller down and stormed out the room.   I threw my head up in shame and was like "dang what did I do!?!?!"  I then spent the next 24 hours doing damage control, apologizing too my friend profusely and offering to pay our mutual friend some $$$ to make sure he didn't say anything.  Ever since then, I've not let a single secret slip.

List and explain the test for ascertaining microbial contamination

Author: OAG-AI
Content:
Sure, here are some common tests used for ascertaining microbial contamination:

1. **Total Viable Count (TVC)**: This test measures the total number of viable microorganisms present in a sample. It provides an overall indication of microbial contamination.

2. **Coliform Test**: Coliform bacteria are commonly found in the intestines of warm-blooded animals. The presence of coliforms in a sample can indicate fecal contamination and the potential presence of other harmful pathogens.

3. **E. coli Test**: Escherichia coli (E. coli) is a type of coliform bacteria that is specifically used as an indicator of fecal contamination in water and food samples. Its presence suggests the possible presence of other harmful bacteria.

4. **Salmonella Test**: Salmonella is a type of bacteria that can cause food poisoning. Testing for the presence of Salmonella in food products is crucial for ensuring food safety.

5. **Staphylococcus aureus Test**: Staphylococcus aureus is a bacterium commonly found on the skin and in the nose of humans. It can produce toxins that cause food poisoning, so testing for its presence is important in food safety.

6. **Yeast and Mold Count**: This test measures the total number of yeast and mold colonies present in a sample. Excessive levels of yeast and mold can indicate spoilage or contamination in food products.

7. **Sterility Test**: This test is used to determine whether a sample is free from viable microorganisms. It is commonly performed on pharmaceutical products, medical devices, and sterile preparations.

These tests are essential for ensuring the safety and quality of various products, including food, water, pharmaceuticals, and cosmetics. Depending on the specific requirements and regulations of different industries, additional tests may be performed to detect and quantify microbial contamination.

Author: cmooney
Content:
$MyStory

So many examples here 😅
1. Save, save, save.
2. Buy XX year CDs.
3. Don’t get a credit card.

I believe that advice is derived from scarcity mindsets and/or from people who are not definite optimists.

My entire mindset changed when I had just started playing online poker. I walked into my bank with a ~$2,000 dollar check to cash from Ultimate Bet. The bank thought the check was fake and that they had “caught a criminal.”

Later that day, my dad (born in 1937) pointed out that banks are just a business. And while many people believe they profit share what they make with their customers (you), the split will never be close to fair. If you can put your money to work elsewhere, do it.

I believe the following is better than the above. 

1. Put it to work in the markets, and understand what % must be able to be liquidated at any time, for your personal expenses (i.e. paying off cc statements).

2. Nowadays liquid CDs exist for a reason. The rates banks were offering on CDs were more easily recognized as not being worth it (inflation, etc. etc. out pacing rate).

3. Credit cards are MUCH safer and have more upside than a debit card, if you understand your credit line is not the number you should freely spend. 

Cash back of up to 4% is insane and adds up. If your cc is compromised, you’re not on the hook as easily as if it were your debit card. They also allow you to have to have less $ sitting in a bank at any given time, thanks to statement cycles. 

And while I don’t enjoy the credit score system, they help build your credit for future purchases and loans, such as a home, which will be the largest asset that 90+% of people strive for and will have in their lifetimes.

If you can’t tell by now, I’m a definite optimist with a chip on my shoulder for banks 😬

Author: cmooney
Content:
$MyStory

When I lived in Dublin, Ireland, I had always heard the Google HQ for Europe was amazing. One day I swung by to ask if they offered tours, to which I was politely told no. 

Flash forward about 2 years later, when I was back in Dublin for the summer and helping map the startup ecosystem. We hosted 2 events at Google; a Startup Weekend & a hackathon focused on marketing. 

During both events, it felt awesome to be in there, watching people build, pitch, and collaborate. 

For the Startup Weekend event, we had a "green room" of sorts. It had what I believed to be UNLIMITED snacks and drinks, with a mix of healthy and sugary. 

One of my friends from those events went on to found the company, Imvizar. AR storytelling platform, now with customers all over the world.

Author: wittytrader_05
Content:
Ahhh, can't resist telling this one😅. My first & only  hackathon was December last year when I finished my Data analysis course at the  boarderless developers program.

So after the program, ayalabs and boarderless hosted a hackathon. It was a group work, where we had to work with graduates from other tech stacks. We were divided into two teams, we had i think about 3 weeks to complete it though but I think we got up to a month. I had my exams that period and since I didn't own P.C I was just praying we had more time. Well luckily for me, my role was needed during the Christmas holidays so I just used my dad's P.C to do a bit brushing up.  

The other team won though. Yeah my team wasn't really coordinated but yeah it was  an amazing experience.

Author: cmooney
Content:
In thinking about the basis of "your network is your net worth," I've started to think about how that's compounded in my life. 

I'd like pay someone to help me create a living/editable graphic that has an x and y axis, showing some key connections that have compounded. 

i.e. in 1995 at the age of 8, I wanted to go to the local comic book store every time I got paid for farm chores. 5 years later, the owner of that store, Jeff Lundsford, helped me to understand and play Magic: The Gathering. That led to compounding connections in the Magic Pro Tour, then Poker, then startups. 

^^ x axis could be year and who. y axis could be something fun, like "wisdom points." 

It'd be amazing if the graph could be super high definition, where you could zoom in on any point, to see expanded info. The zoom out would keep it simple with points being the year, name, etc.

If you're interested in helping with this, please message me and include any past design for visualizations you've created. Will pay $/ETH.

I still need to get this project up and going again, but had a friend working on some ways to visualize my life in graphs. Maybe take this as inspiration. https://mschneider247.github.io/Clayton_Graphs/

Author: omnianalytics
Content:
$MyStory

The purpose of the <#1159298067917439086>  channel is for us all to get to know one another through the experience of sharing interesting stories about our lives.  We put in quite a lot of effort into creating the prompts, but not all of them are going to relevant to you, and that's ok! If you have a fun story to share that you think others would enjoy, please do. Otherwise, give others a chance to share.

For now, let's take a break from doing payouts for a while to rekindle the true spirit of the channel. Upvotes stories will get Kudos and we'll bring back payouts later.

Author: omnianalytics
Content:
In the spirit of transparency and to elaborate just a tad bit more on the culture I'm trying to establish around here, let me address the people farming the Story Sharing bot.  

<@1223293376066097204> , <@1231632377743147096> and <@1233898686031990827> (and others)  

I actually didn't have a real issue with you all posting daily to get a little bit of crypto into your tip.cc accounts and, in some ways, it is encouraged around here.  We, on purpose, made the system pretty lax so that just simple upvoting by the community would enable the bot to release funds.  This incentivizes people to post stories and, likewise, gets others engaged to read them. The problem was you all started to overtly game the system by posting responses that were too short, weren't descriptive, and overall low effort.  On top of that, you all would upvote each other to guarantee payouts.  Colluding for payouts wouldn't have been so bad if not for the posts themselves being low effort.  We tried to highlight this by increasing the number of votes to receive payouts as a gentle way of saying "hey you all, you are breaking the spirit of the channel", but the result was a more strengthened effort to collude amongst you all.  For that we had to do enforce the rules.  

My suggestion, hang out around here, learn about crypto, and share interesting stories out of the kindness of your heart to help us restore the intent of this channel.

Author: .djw.
Content:
$MyStory 
It all started when I was born. I was born at a very young age. I became a child. I was just like everyone else, I've always been different. Regarding fitness I started when I was really overweight as a kid in high school, around 16. Joined the track and field team, did shot put, discus, javelin. I got really good at it, got first in conference my senior year after only training for like 1 year. Then I started weight lifting and bodybuilding. Dropped from 265lbs to 185 at 5'10ish from junior to senior year high school. Then started building back up to about 200lbs. Did powerlifting 5x5's until I hit 1plate overhead press 2plate bench 3plate squat and 4plate deadlift for 5 sets of 5 reps with good form. Took my about 2 years of consistent lifting. And cardio everyday. At least 30 min on the bike. 150min a week for heart health. Then I started getting into more advanced training methods and periodization. Now I just do yoga and am trying to learn martial arts. I still lift, but it isn't my life.

Author: omnianalytics
Content: ""Tornado Cash does not pose any barrier for people with criminal assets who want to launder them," according to the translated verdict seen by CoinDesk. "That is why the court regards the defendant guilty of the money laundering activities as charged."" <-- that's the problem with this verdict in one paragraph.  They basically hold devlopers responsible for what they publish on the blockchain.

Author: drcpu
Content: I have not read the actual verdict, so I don't know to what extent they distinguish between the TC frontend and the actual contracts.

Author: drcpu
Content: To some extent, I follow the notion that if you offer a frontend which is totally under your control, you are liable for what people do with it.

Author: drcpu
Content: The contracts on the blockchain however, if they are immutable, is mostly outside of your control, and it would be a pretty bad precedent of those are also considered as offering an illegal service.

Author: omnianalytics
Content: Good point, but I don't think they truely cared about that nuanced.  They found the people who deployed the contract and that seems to be the crux.  Like, do you think that if there was no front end that it wouldn't matter?  They'd be perfectly fine with the tool being out there?

Author: drcpu
Content: I don't know, I have not read the verdict, so I don't actually know what he has been found guilty of.

Author: omnianalytics
Content: hehehe me either, we are speculating 🙂

Author: drcpu
Content: I can perfectly see the verdict saying he's guilty of offering TC as a service (as in the frontend), and Coindesk summarizing that as the whole protocol. 😉

Author: drcpu
Content: Probably no one from the prosecution likes the tool, but finding someone guilty for writing and publishing open source software is pretty far reaching verdict.

Author: drcpu
Content: I would expect there being a lot of precedent that just writing software is not bad, even if it can be used for illegal things. Otherwise, most people working on encryption software and the likes are next.

Author: drcpu
Content: If the latter has happened, I cannot imagine it holding up at higher courts.

Author: cmooney
Content:
$MyStory

I've been obsessed with Universal Basic Income (UBI) for years.

Pros: you can unlock people's creative potential.
Cons: you may lose all of the money, because people may not find motivation.

I think you should approach it capitalistically.

You start with open applications. People show you what they're creating. 

You then select the most promising people and pay their year's worth of bills/salary. You structure it something like $40k-$100k. They choose the amount within that range, and then you receive equity of between 8%-20%. $40k = 8%. $100k = 20%. Essentially $500k post money valuation. 

I want to do this. I've thought about when I can afford to. I took inspiration from the Thiel Fellowship, and I felt like there would come a time where AI tools could handle most of the back office things (legal + bookkeeping + benchmarking). 

But how could it grow exponentially? DAO is the answer.

Why? 

DAOs are first a community. Second, they're (hopefully) all wanting similar results. 

How would it work? 

I'll begin by creating the Mooney Fellowship. My wife (Mikayla) and I open up applications nationally for 6 months. We take 6 months to review, interview, accept. We then select our first Fellow & invest between $40k-$100k into them. A 12 month timeline helps focus on people who are thinking longer term.

You then create a community chat like here. You provide resources and be a good mentor (1. you tell them what they need to hear, when they need to hear it. 2. you make your network their network.).

As you bring on more & more fellows and ultimately have cohorts, everyone has access to this community. 

As fellows find success and have more financial freedom, you offer to let them invest in future fellows alongside you. 

AI tools keep overhead low. Community all has skin in the game. Voting and direction of the DAO is driven by members, but the starting mission will be making the world a better place through art or technology. That's what we love.

Content:
Jumping into Blast.

What is it? It’s an Ethereum L2, built by Pacman, the Founder of Blur. 
Blur is an NFT marketplace for professional traders.

What drew me to Blast...
Earlier this year, I was continuing to stake AVAX but felt overwhelmed by the AVAX community and where to start, if I wanted to jump into a Discord/forum.

I went on the search for a community building in the art and/or gaming space. 

I came across New Blast City on Twitter. I joined their Discord. I started to learn about how Blast had just launched February 29. It had > $1b TVL when I discovered about 1 week later. 

New Blast City’s Discord had a lot of people who have been in the web3 space for the past 8+ years. The dialogue wasn’t just filled with GMs and degen links. 

I posted a lot about my play in New Blast City in the NFT channel earlier, but I’ve since gone WAY down the Blast rabbit hole.

Their Token Generation Event (TGE) is scheduled for June 26. 

They’re doing a big airdrop from people’s points and gold earned in the Blast ecosystem. You earn from interacting with and owning assets built on Blast, such as New Blast City. I believe it’ll be the largest airdrop by $ value this year. Currently, people are speculating that ~35,000 Blast points = 1 gold. 1 gold = ~$10.

Author: cmooney
Content:
Not unlimited money, but picking winners who have the most growth potential.

It’s like angel investing at a friends and family round, except you don’t want or need there to be a liquidity event. You want them to build a profitable business and pay dividends to you, their partner. You are investing in their entity.

In angel investing, most of your bets go to zero. 

End goal of UBI is to have people not having to worry about how to pay their rent and grocery bills. I think that’s too utopian. I think my model only chooses the best (although I’ll be wrong the majority of the time) candidates. Selection will be similar to Venture Capital. Of every 100 people who are likely qualified, there will only be 1 person selected/invested in.

Author: omnianalytics
Content: In a true "mixed economy", the economy America is attempting to abide by, you grant everyone the individual freedom to embark on the tasks that they find most fulfilling and economically productive while the government plays the role of referee whose primary responsibility is to maintain the integrity of the game and structure of the economy.

Author: omnianalytics
Content: What we are observing with this talk of inflation and the sudden need of UBI is a result of unfettered capitalism taking hold of the reigns with the government and its quasi-independent institutions, like the Federal Reserve, reacting on the back foot.

Author: omnianalytics
Content: Those in advantageous positions often realize that one of the quickest ways to not only gain an extra advantage over their competition, but secure profits over the long term is to lobby Congress and influence legislation.  The ways they do this all have the same end result...the structure and integrity of the mixed economy gets compromised.

Author: omnianalytics
Content: So now you have corporations that can take any set of actions to increase their profit margins.  Think shoddy products, employee exploitation, lack of pollution controls, price exploitation and, basically any and every negative externality you can think of.

Author: omnianalytics
Content: That lack of regulation is everywhere, even in banking, which allows the banks to over leverage their deposits in a way that, should they get in trouble, the losses have to be subsidized through inflationary means taken by the Federal Reserve.

Author: omnianalytics
Content:
So despite things seemingly being well structured, you have corporations effectively able to do anything and the government is not able to strategize nor focus on a clear plan that restores the economy back into a form that reestablishes young people's ability to get jobs, provide for themselves, and build a future.  
Interestingly enough, there are always smart people who, purely acting on economic incentive, will be able to exploit the system and thrive in the chaos.  These people are the ones that can still achieve and live the "American Dream".  The problem is that dream is less and less attainable as it requires much more skill and risk taking to maneuver through the structural traps of corporate exploitation and government mismanagement of its power.

Author: omnianalytics
Content: So that gets us to the situation we're in now where people are suggesting a Universal Basic Income as the fix.  For better or for worse, if the government doesn't assume its proper role and move us back to a well structured mixed economy with opportunities and societal safety nets, a UBI will be NECESSARY because as AI, robotics and other emerging technologies mature and become entrenched in our lives, they will create "winner take all" scenarios where the best AI, best robotics, and overall best industry participants make all the money.

Author: omnianalytics
Content: We see this already with start-up generating more and more revenue with fewer and fewer employees.  With AI that trend is only going to get worse.   Under those conditions you'll have TONS of unemployed people with no reasonable way to upskill because, who is going to be smarter than AI in 2 years? No one 🥲

Author: omnianalytics
Content: As George said, we can hope people are less greedy, but we can't count on that.

Author: omnianalytics
Content: That means that the government is likely to let the rules of the game continue to lax, but put in the quickest fix which is to increase taxes to redistribute money to everyone to provide basic services.  It likely won't be just UBI but other universal style programs that provide important services.

Author: omnianalytics
Content: Why?  Because incumbents are going to be so far entrenched in their positions and it will be increasingly more and more difficult to achieve upward mobility due to the complexity of getting a job where you are competing against or must learn how to manage AI or build  a company that provides a service in a niche that companies with AI and robots can't overtake you.

Author: omnianalytics
Content: This brings us to yesterday's topic..."What role will DAOs play in the future?"

Author: omnianalytics
Content: I believe community will be VERY important in the future as people realize they themselves as individuals have much less control and influence than they believe and that one of the best ways to actually achieve upward mobility will be to work with and along side a group of like minded people.

Author: omnianalytics
Content: Judd alluded to this ... "Everyone works together to make businesses successful, everyone should get rewarded when times are good, not just the top."

Author: omnianalytics
Content: As things get tougher and tougher, people will start looking for tribes they can join for support, meaning and opportunities.  We actually see this trend a lot with youtube influencers starting Discord channels and Patreons.  Those that join will want to have a voice and to coordinate all of the various activities, the technological innovations that web3 affords DAOs will be front in center as tokens and other smart contracts are used to boost positive contributions and regulate the negative.

Author: omnianalytics
Content: Successful DAOs will be able to leverage their network to the benefit of its members, creating a flywheel effect that brings in value for the members which bring in more members and those members contribute in a way that provides value and the cycle repeats.

Author: omnianalytics
Content: TL:DR - UBI is coming and while it creeps in slowly, DAOs will grow in influence and mature into economically viable digital communities that provide value capture for its members while sustaining and promoting its cultural values in perpetuity via AI and smart contracts.

Author: .djw.
Content:
$MyStory
I was meditating yesterday practicing for something very important, and it required my total concentration for a span of 1.5hrs. At the 1.15hr mark, I felt a disturbance and it was probably my roommate dropping something outside my door and that almost made me feel like the entire session had been wasted and I was about to be really frustrated. 
Then I realized that had it not been my roommate dropping something, then perhaps a siren or another loud noise, or some other disturbance would have taken its place. Literally anything could have happened at any time to have disrupted my focus, and then I realized that the actual thing itself did not matter. The disruption itself could have taken place in any way, shape, time, or form. And in recognizing that, you can also learn to let it go. 
Because it could have happened in any way, then that necessarily means that the actual thing you are mad or frustrated about does not matter in so much as the underlying event matters. So redirecting frustration to the actual point event that is fated can help you see that there is nothing to be mad about to begin with. It is like getting mad that the sun rises or flowers bloom. Everything is cause and effect, but your reaction to it ought to be like water flowing under a passage or like the clouds forming the weather. 
So uh ultimately handling frustration poorly is merely because of becloudings we deceive ourselves with because of a lack of perspective. Frustration never touches the balanced and unclouded mind, though it may reach toward it.

Author: omnianalytics
Content:
$MyStory

Surviving in chaos boils down to 4 things: 1) Staying alive 😅  2) Staying poised 3) Collecting information 4) Making sense of the information you've gathered.  1 and 2 are often interchangeable because if you can't stay composed you don't stay alive and if you you are already gone, no reason to worry staying poised 🥲 .  During the "Fog of War", "Knowledge is Power" and those who have a better understanding of what happening and what happens next tend to be those that make it out.  There is randomness involved in chaos, but if you can managed to have lady luck on yourside and a solid game plan you'll actually thrive in the uncertainty.

$MyStory

For me I try to take out a moment to decide and not let the situation overwhelm me, whether i should or should not act and getting ready to accept what ever comes out of it, coz you'll never know was at the end of the pathway in chaotic situation. Author: .djw.
Content: because you can't say how you are going to act until faced with that situation

Author: .djw.
Content: all our speculation is in vein

Content: we should all do the navy seal training, where they tie you to a chair and kick you into freezing water

Author: .djw.

Author: omnianalytics
Content:
Nawl, that's not necessarily true for two reasons Dyllon... 1.  That's what training is for...so that when you are faced with a chaotic unexpected situation you can fall back on your training and in this case...the training we are all proporting is to "stay calm" 2. some of us have been in really tough unexpected situations, me for one, and I can undoubtedly tell you that mental training that I had unexpectedly done prior to those situations helped me and it was the reason why I had positive outcomes.

So it is possible to provide answers to this, based both on theory crafting and experience

Author: .djw.
Content: I would like to agree, but I just went shopping and in the vitamin aisle I was looking for something that was not there, and there was another old dude there, and I felt the panic judgement response from him as if he were judging me for not knowing what I was doing. My pupils dilate and I feel pins on my forehead and begin to sweat a little. It's purely psycho-somatic, I know I was in no danger and that he was not even paying attention to me, but its just there because I've had that engrained in me for so long that it is the normal response.

Content: So I probably cannot say with certainty that I even know my own self well enough to articulate what I would do when faced with an unknown

Content: Recognizing it is the first step then, just like all of the other ways you work out, you practice controlling it. Content: The opponent knows that as well and what tends to happen is both players get sloppy because they want to get that last hit....

Author: cmooney
Content:
$MyStory

I'm obsessed with the fellowship model, which could eventually become a DAO in itself. 

For governance and if I had to launch one tomorrow, it'd be similar and parallel a CAP table/ownership of a company. Everyone would be vesting and given tokens would have the similar voting % of their ownership. 

i.e. 

Omniacs DAO launches tomorrow. I want to contribute 1% of the treasury. Everyone agrees that the treasury is 100 ETH.

I contribute 1 ETH. But I don't have 1% vote right now. It vests over the coming 48 months. The first 12 months, if I stop contibuting/leave, I am only given my 1 ETH back and all my ownership is burned (1 year cliff). At month 13, it starts vesting monthly, and I'm 13/48 vested to my 1% ownership/voting. 

As the treasury expands and more people come on board with similar vesting, it forces everyone to think long term and put in the work to have the vote.

Author: 254karan
Content:
$MyStory
You say smile and I think  of the
day  my niece  was born. Not only  did  I smile but it change my life and mentality  forever. 
So before  she was born  I really used to dislike  small kids given  that I was also  a kid. I used to mishandle kids and even beat them . But since she was born it changed alot and I became fond of kids. I literally used  to carry her photos  in my school  bag . I was so proud  I would  show everyone  her photos.  All I thought  of doing  was saving  up money  and buying her tiny ,pretty clothes.  The day she was born gave  me a huge smile and changed my life.

Author: cmooney
Content:
$MyStory

The time is now to embrace unlearning (adapt) & to define your identity (control your narrative). Technology is compounding and will leave those who don't, behind.

i.e. 1: My wife & I bought an acreage about 2 years ago. A year ago, we used DIY YouTube to fix everything from a bathroom sink to improving efficiency of cooling the house with our heat pump. In the past 3 months, we've utilized the ChatGPT app to change the oil on our riding lawnmower, & how to best put up and secure fence for the barn animals. Family members thought we needed to buy a trailer to haul the mower to town, & we even thought that we may need to hire a professional to come in and help put up the fence. 

i.e. 2: For Clayton Farms, our main investor and mentor has seen a lot. About 6 months before my other networks were talking about it, he told me to unlearn VC funding = growth and hiring. To begin thinking about which tools were better to utilize and how they could scale, instead of hiring. Today, I do the job of 3 of our past full-time team members. With not enough hours in the day, & the constraint on resources (time and $), I've replaced those positions w/Canva AI, CapCut, & automations. I'm now seeing peers' companies shut down, because they still have too high of burn rate & all of those positions are still full-time people. 

i.e. 3: Many younger people are stating they want to be an influencer for a career. They post on YouTube and Instagram every day. We all know an "influencer." There is no specific subject they focus on. Their rhetoric is all fluff + buzz words. When you ask them who they are influencing, they often times say that they're helping people to <insert fluff inspirational quote or hot market subject, such as AI or crypto>. That is shiny object syndrome, & the complete opposite of having an identity. 

Since everyone can publish content, you have 2 choices. Control your narrative and discuss what you care about. Or let someone else/the market do it for you.

Author: .djw.
Content:
$MyStory 
Breathing. Yes breathing is a skill. Most people do not have it.

Every second of your life you are breathing. Most people do this unconsciously and a lot of times incorrectly. There's the stereotype against "mouth breathers" for a good reason. Mouth breathing is bad posture, it can mess with jaw and cranium development and sleep and life. 
 
Controlling your breathing is controlling your focus. Even hearing briefly about and trying some techniques like Pranayama will yield blessings 10 fold. 

When you inhale, God enters you. When you hold the inhale, God dwells within you. When you exhale, you approach God. When you hold the exhale, you surrender to God. 

Lowers blood pressure, sharpens your mind, increase oxygen uptake, lots of benefits to even 5 min of controlled focused breathing. 

And if you're a little bit mentally eccentric, you can look into Qigong, or chi manipulation. Using breathing to channel life energy into various actions...

Author: k.aran_
Content:
$MyStory 
My friend had a farm house that we really enjoy going to some weekends. The farm house is within a tea plantation and has a river at the end of the tea plantation and on the other side . So on this particular weekend we decided to go down to the river coz we never got that far . It is was the most spectacular view and the water was chill and the surrounding was still , so peaceful down there . We played in the water and while we were there it started raining , we danced barefoot  in the rain and it was a really wholesome experience that I had not experienced in a while.  It really brought out the little child in me and I've always been so glad to join them on the trip upcountry to the farm house . Who knew dancing in the rain could be so refreshing .
